                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d859">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/17923: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-27T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 27, 1941—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 27—11:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Sir Stafford Cripps informed me this morning that he has resigned his post as
                    Ambassador and plans to return to England. I inferred that he contemplates
                    reentering political life there.</p>
                <p>With respect to Japan, Cripps expressed the opinion that the Soviet Union is not
                    now in a position to engage Japan successfully and that by entering the war in
                    the Pacific it would weaken the effort against Germany. He added however that he
                    believes that Russia will be at war with Japan within 3 months and implied that
                    the Soviet Government both expects and desires that hostilities shall be
                    initiated by the Japanese.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
